  "prompt": "What is the risk of intercaste marriage and honour killing in bihar?",
  "response": "In Bihar, like some other parts of India, intercaste marriages can face social challenges and risks:\n\n1. Social Stigma:\n- Strong caste-based social hierarchies\n- Potential family and community opposition\n- Social ostracism for couples\n\n2. Honour Killing Risks:\n- Some conservative communities view intercaste marriages as threatening traditional social structures\n- Higher risk in rural areas with more rigid caste systems\n- Families might resort to violence to \"protect\" perceived family honor\n\n3. Statistical Context:\n- Bihar has reported incidents of honour killings\n- Exact statistics vary, but risks are higher in rural and socially conservative regions\n\n4. Legal Protections:\n- Special Marriage Act allows intercaste marriages\n- Supreme Court and government discourage honour killings\n- Legal provisions against honor crimes exist\n\n5. Reducing Risks:\n- Increasing education\n- Urban exposure\n- Younger generation's changing attitudes\n- Support from progressive social organizations\n\nWhile risks exist, societal attitudes are gradually changing, especially among younger, more educated populations.\n\nNote: Specific statistics can vary, and situations differ across different regions of Bihar.",
